does google gemini cli run on the fish shell

Gemini said
Yes, the Google Gemini CLI can run within the Fish shell.

Since the official Gemini CLI (often invoked as gemini) is a Node.js-based application, it is generally shell-agnostic. However, because Fish uses a different syntax for environment variables and scripting compared to Bash or Zsh, there are a few specific "Fish-friendly" ways to set it up.

🚀 Installation on Fish
You can install the CLI using npm or Homebrew, both of which work perfectly in a Fish environment.

Via npm:

Code snippet
npm install -g @google/gemini-cli
Via Homebrew:

Code snippet
brew install gemini-cli
🔑 Setting Environment Variables
The most common point of friction with Fish is setting the required API keys or Project IDs. Fish does not use the export VAR=val syntax used in Bash.

To set variables for the current session:
Code snippet
set -x GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT "your-project-id"
set -x GEMINI_API_KEY "your-api-key"
To make them persistent (Recommended):
Add these lines to your Fish configuration file (usually located at ~/.config/fish/config.fish):

Code snippet
set -gx GOOGLE_CLOUD_PROJECT "your-project-id"
set -gx GEMINI_API_KEY "your-api-key"
(The -g flag makes it global, and -x exports it so the Gemini CLI process can see it.)

🛠️ Integration Features
The Gemini CLI includes a run_shell_command tool that allows the AI to execute terminal commands.

Platform Behavior: On macOS and Linux, the CLI typically spawns commands using bash -c. This means that even if you are inside Fish, the specific sub-commands Gemini runs might follow Bash syntax unless configured otherwise.

Interactive Mode: You can use the --yolo flag if you want Gemini to execute shell commands in your Fish terminal without asking for confirmation every time (use with caution!).

💡 Pro Tip: fish-ai
If you are looking for a more "native" experience, there is a popular community plugin called fish-ai. It is specifically designed for Fish and allows you to:

Turn comments into Fish commands using Ctrl+P.

Fix broken commands in your history.

Use Gemini (via API key) as the backend provider.





